        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4935.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Russel Wallace</ref> had asked Weir to carry out experiments to test Wallace’s theory that brightly coloured caterpillars would be refused by birds (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 15, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5416.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from A. R. Wallace, 24 February [1867]</ref> and n. 4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><hi rend="italic">Vanessa io</hi>, the peacock butterfly, is now <hi rend="italic">Inachis io</hi>; <hi rend="italic">V. urticae</hi>, the small tortoiseshell butterfly, is now <hi rend="italic">Aglais urticae</hi>. These species have black and black and yellow caterpillars respectively.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Porthesia auriflua</hi> is now <hi rend="italic">Sphrageidus similis</hi>; the yellow-tail, <hi rend="italic">Spilosoma menthastri</hi>, is now <hi rend="italic">S. lubricipeda</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Caterpillars of <hi rend="italic">Spilosoma menthastri</hi> are black with long brown hairs and an orange stripe down the back.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Females of <hi rend="italic">Orgyia antiqua</hi> have only rudimentary wings and relatively large bodies and therefore have very limited mobility. They deposit their eggs on the outside of the cocoon.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">The geodephaga are a tribe of terrestrial and predaceous beetles (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5936.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">OED</hi></ref>); the family Blattae is now known as Blattidae.</note>
        </div>        
            
